node.text: It was never about what she got from basketball. It was always about what she gave back. Gigi gave inspiration to her teammates, her mentors, and the next generation. #PlayGigisWay @mambamambacitasports

node.text:
Tiger would. Would you?
Break barriers. Set records. Play through pain and never call it a comeback. 

Tiger is never done.

ADVANTAGE, @rafaelnadal. 
 
1. FIRST SLAM ONLY NINETEEN YEARS OLD. 
2. SECOND SLAM. 
3. THIRD SLAM.
4. STILL UNDEFEATED ON CLAY.
5. GREATEST GAME EVER. FIVE SET THRILLER TO CLAIM FIRST TROPHY AWAY FROM CLAY. THEN THE GOLD MEDAL.
6. FIRST HARD COURT SLAM AT AUS.
7.  BACK TO WINNING WAYS ON CLAY. 
8. SECOND WIN AT SW19.
9. FIRST TRIUMPH AT FLUSHING MEADOWS MEANS TROPHY CABINET IS NOW FULL. 
10. 6TH FRENCH.
11. RECORD BREAKING SEVENTH FRENCH. 
12. RECORD EXTENDING EIGHTH FRENCH. 
13. SECOND US.
14. MOST CONSECUTIVE FRENCH TITLES BUT WHAT FOLLOWS IS TWO YEARS WITHOUT WINNING A TROPHY. IS IT THE END OF HIS CAREER? 
15. DEFIES THE DOUBTERS BY BECOMING THE ONLY MAN TO WIN TEN TROPHIES IN A SINGLE SLAM. 
16. THIRD US. 
17. RECORD EXTENDING ELEVENTH FRENCH.
18. RECORD EXTENDING TWELFTH FRENCH.
19. FIVE SET EPIC US TITLE. 
20 RECORD EQUALING 20TH SLAM. 
 
DEUCE. 
 
21. ADVANTAGE, NADAL.

node.text:
“It doesn’t matter where you start because when you play to lift your people, no hoop is too high.” 

The world may know @giannis_an34 as an MVP and NBA champion, but it’s his work off the court that’s truly special. 

The AntetokounBros Academy is more than basketball, it’s a space where kids from diverse backgrounds are given the chance to unleash and develop their potential through sport. Where everyone and anyone feels they belong. 

With the help of @onassis.stegi and @eurohoops_official, Giannis has created something that he never had growing up. A place where you’re encouraged to follow your passion and where having fun is as important as working hard. On or off the court, one thing is for certain, Giannis is Never Done changing the game.

“When you figure out what makes you happy, you gotta keep doing it because you’re gonna be the best version of yourself.”

🎥 @hael_ky
📸 @eleni.albarosa
🎨 @nique.one

node.text:
“My generation is all about being brave, being strong, and doing it because you love it.” - @skybrown

Sky, the world’s youngest pro skateboarder, pushes her limits in all the best ways. Whether she’s in a park 🛹, on the water 🏄‍♀️, or dancing on national television 💃, Sky is proof that radical optimism isn’t a weakness — it’s a superpower.

Tag a friend who is an optimist like Sky. 😎☀️

node.text:
Short-track speed skating is not for the faint of heart. That’s why it’s perfect for @sukiouob. 

South Korea’s beloved “Queen of Short Track” is a world champ and brave advocate for survivors of abuse. 💪🥇 By speaking up, Suk-hee made sport safer for women. And now she wants all young athletes to know “a turning point is not what we wait for, but what we make. We have the power to do that.”

✨ Know a powerful woman like Suk-hee? Tag them in the comments below. ✨

node.text:
“I think the biggest thing you can do is inspire somebody and give them hope that it’s possible to get what you want.” — @dbook 

We all know NBA All-Star Devin Booker as the incredible athlete he is on the court. Now, he’s striving to give back to his community—this time through his “Devin Booker Starting Five” program. From helping rebuild local courts to providing funding for educational programs and helping special needs groups, Devin is committed to putting team and community first. 🇲🇽🏀💪

Join us in celebrating Latino Heritage Month with Devin and let us know what impact your starting five is making in your community in the comments below.

node.text:
The future of skateboarding is here. Just ask thirteen-year-old @rayssalealsk8. 

With several international victories under her belt, Rayssa represents a new era of the sport that’s open to all…even little girls wearing sparkly wings. With her skater-girl-magic on deck, she’s ready to help usher in a new era of sport. ✨🧚‍♀️

node.text:
50 years of Nike.

50 years of athletes helping athletes. 50 years of becoming stronger, faster, and more dynamic. 50 years of making mistakes, and becoming better from it.

And if we’ve learned anything from the past, it’s that we’re in for a hell of a future. #Nike50

node.text:
"When you're on top of one mountain, you're really on the bottom of the next, right?" @tatyanamcfaddenusa

Ever since Tatyana McFadden’s debut at the Paralympics at age 15, she has steadily risen to the top of her sport in wheelchair track and field and marathoning. With a 2017 diagnosis and recovery from a blood clotting disorder (one that caused her to pull out of this year’s Boston Marathon) Tatyana has been afforded the opportunity to re-evaluate—her training, her goals, the things in life that bring her joy. She is proving that progress may be a continual challenge, but it’s one worth taking on.
 
Never done reinventing. 🔝
 
Click the link in bio to learn more about what Tatyana is working on.

node.text:
Ever wonder what happens to the Nike shoes you return? If you’re in North America, they end up here at Nike Rebound, our reverse logistics facility in Indiana.

Not too long ago, all returns that weren’t in mint condition were recycled as part of Nike Grind. But now, thanks to the Nike Refurbished program and the work of expert sneaker cleaners, more than 225,000 pairs and counting are making it back onto shelves at a reduced price in select stores. Want to learn more about their journey? Click the link in our bio.

Brought to you by Move to Zero: Nike’s journey toward zero carbon and zero waste to help protect the future of sport.

📷 @arielfish

node.text:
Ever since her Paralympic debut at age 15, @tatyanamcfaddenusa has steadily risen to the top of her sport. From her beginnings as a wheelchair sprinter to becoming one of the world’s fastest wheelchair marathoners, the 32-year-old has defied every expectation placed on her.

Sadly, the 2017 diagnosis and recovery from a blood clotting disorder caused her to pull out of this year’s Boston Marathon. Ever the optimist, Tatyana is using this as an opportunity to adjust her training and spend more time with the things she enjoys in life as she prepares for her next race.

Never done reinventing.

node.text:
Up until 2020, @ahegerberg felt invincible. The Lyon striker was at the top of her game, with a long list of accolades: She received the first women’s Ballon d’Or prize and has hoisted the Champions League trophy four times. Then, for the first time in her career, she became injured. Nearly as challenging as her excruciating physical recovery was finding the patience to slow down and let her body heal.

Never done evolving. 💪

"Football being taken away from me has been one of the most difficult things I've experienced throughout my career and life. I am not a patient person." @ahegerberg 

Patience doesn't come easy, especially when you're one of the greatest young talents ever to play the game. However, Norwegian footballer Ada Hegerberg learned a lot about herself and life during her difficult injury period. She's now back on the pitch with a whole new perspective.

Click the link in bio to learn more about what Ada is working on.

node.text:
How do you update a classic shoe with more environmentally preferred materials, without messing with what made it great? With data, of course! Since about 70% of Nike’s carbon footprint comes from materials, knowing what you use to make a shoe has a big impact.

Follow the link in our bio to see how team members including designers, material developers, data analysts and more used informed decision making to reinvent icons with more than 20% recycled content by weight.

Brought to you by Move to Zero: Nike’s Journey toward zero carbon and zero waste to help protect the future of sport.

📷 @arielfish
